	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Financing the new common fisheries policy: two new instruments are to be developed</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The EU Agriculture and Fisheries Council held its first policy debate on the Commission proposal for a European Fisheries Fund (EFF) for the period 2007-2013 on November 24th 2004. There were divergent views among member states in a number of areas, such as funding for the building of new vessels, restricting aid to small and micro-enterprises in aquaculture and the compulsory provision of social and economic aid measures.</p><p> The EFF, with a budget of Euro4,963 million, is designed to help implement measures towards securing sustainable fisheries and diversifying economic activities in the EU's fishery sector.</p><p> The EFF is one of two fisheries financial instruments proposed by the EC in its July communication 'Financial Perspectives 2007-2013'. The second instrument, for which a proposal has yet to be presented, 'would gather together all the areas where the Common Fisheries Policy needs finance to support CFP reform:</p>
<ul>

<li>investment in control measures to allow modern control techniques to be put in place in all controlled waters, and back up the work of the fisheries control agency; </li>

<li>measures to promote high quality and easily available scientific advice and technical data; </li>

<li>provision for the conclusion and financing of international fisheries agreements and participation in regional fisheries organisations.'</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/press/inf04_47_en.htm" target="_self">DG Fisheries press release</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/doc_et_publ/factsheets/legal_texts/docscom/en/com_04_497_en.pdf" target="_self">EC proposal for a regulation on a European Fisheries Fund, COM(2004) 497...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://folk.uio.no/erikro/WWW/corrgr/insurance/EUfinpersp.pdf" target="_self">EC: 'Financial Perspectives 2007-2013' (for fisheries, see pp. 17-18), C...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Following the reform of the CFP, the EU is now establishing the necessary financial instruments to finance its new proposals. Previously the financial instrument for fisheries guidance (FIFG) provided the means, amongst other things, to subsidise fishing vessel transfers under joint ventures with third countries, including ACP countries.</p><p> A number of important principles are enshrined in the EFF proposal, including improved participation of stakeholders; priority support for small and micro-businesses and coastal fishing areas; support for fishing-gear selectivity and environmentally-friendly practices; improvement of safety, working conditions and product hygiene on board fishing vessels; etc</p><p> The EFF proposal explicitly includes the possibility of funding vessel transfers to third countries, but its Article 15 (d) recommends that 'particular regard' be paid to 'the fisheries product-supply strategy and the development of fishing activities outside the Community waters' as part of the national strategic plans. The interpretation of this article is of paramount importance for ACP countries' fisheries sectors, and has implications for the development of FPAs.</p><p> The proposal states that 'financial support will also be provided for the development of processing activities in the EU'. Support for such activities should not be at the expense of reducing support to developing country fish-processing sectors, and reducing developing country capacity to attract value-adding activities (for example through joint ventures for processing) in their countries.</p><p> Interestingly, whilst the 'Financial Perspectives' and the EFF proposal were produced almost simultaneously in mid-2004, nothing has yet been published about the second fisheries fund. The provisions of the second fund, as outlined in the former, are highly relevant for ACP countries. They are to cover such areas as the conclusion and the financing of international fisheries agreements and participation in RFOs.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
